WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:03.360
You know, I want to start today by asking you a riddle.

00:03.480 --> 00:05.000
Oh, okay. Lay it on me.

00:05.260 --> 00:08.980
And for you, the listener, I want you to really think about this as we go.

00:09.600 --> 00:13.640
It sounds like the setup to a highly specific, very nerdy joke.

00:13.740 --> 00:13.980
Right.

00:14.160 --> 00:16.220
But it actually unlocks one of the most, I mean,

00:16.860 --> 00:20.660
truly mind-bending conceptual frameworks we've ever encountered on a deep dive.

00:21.060 --> 00:22.900
So here is the riddle.

00:22.980 --> 00:23.400
All righty.

00:23.860 --> 00:28.500
What do a single photon briefly turning into an atomic excitation,

00:28.500 --> 00:32.360
a theoretical computer science operation called beta reduction,

00:33.260 --> 00:35.200
the way a human being makes an analogy,

00:35.760 --> 00:39.000
and the turbulence of a chaotic fluid all have in common?

00:39.460 --> 00:39.800
Wow.

00:40.040 --> 00:45.360
I mean, on the surface, that sounds like a list of just entirely unrelated phenomena.

00:45.900 --> 00:48.160
You got, what, quantum physics, abstract mathematics,

00:48.380 --> 00:50.260
cognitive psychology, and fluid dynamics.

00:50.620 --> 00:52.140
Most people would look at those four things

00:52.140 --> 00:56.120
and assume they require completely different vocabularies to even discuss, you know?

00:56.260 --> 00:57.660
Right, let alone actually connect them.

00:57.680 --> 00:58.080
Exactly.

00:58.080 --> 00:59.320
And normally, I would agree.

00:59.760 --> 01:03.280
But today, we are going to explore this wild new framework

01:03.280 --> 01:08.000
that claims to unite all of those under one single hidden blueprint.

01:08.320 --> 01:10.720
It's ambitious, to say the least.

01:10.780 --> 01:11.420
It really is.

01:11.740 --> 01:14.900
We are looking at a framework called the admissibility principle.

01:15.180 --> 01:15.500
Yeah.

01:15.800 --> 01:20.080
And the core argument here is that the universe,

01:20.800 --> 01:23.280
whether we're talking about human thought, artificial intelligence,

01:23.280 --> 01:30.560
or like the literal fabric of space-time relies on a singular master grammar to reorganize itself.

01:30.560 --> 01:33.360
Right, to decide what is allowed to exist, basically.

01:33.520 --> 01:33.700
Yeah.

01:33.700 --> 01:37.140
And the sheer scale of that claim is what makes it so compelling to dig into.

01:37.380 --> 01:37.620
For sure.

01:37.700 --> 01:42.940
The author, Fliction, proposes this universal mechanism called admissibility-constrained collapse.

01:43.320 --> 01:47.660
It's an attempt to describe the fundamental operation of reality updating itself.

01:47.720 --> 01:48.680
Which is huge.

01:48.820 --> 01:49.200
It is.

01:49.200 --> 01:53.340
But before we get too swept up in the grandeur of a theory of everything,

01:53.340 --> 01:54.920
we have to establish some guardrails.

01:55.140 --> 02:00.320
Because the paper itself is extremely disciplined about separating peer-reviewed empirical science

02:00.320 --> 02:01.680
from speculative theory.

02:01.880 --> 02:02.580
Which is crucial.

02:03.020 --> 02:05.940
Because whenever you start talking about grand unifying theories,

02:06.340 --> 02:08.940
it's very easy to fall into a couple of classic traps.

02:08.960 --> 02:09.500
Oh, absolutely.

02:09.500 --> 02:15.620
In the notes, there's this heavy warning against what the author calls premature literalism.

02:16.140 --> 02:19.060
That's the mistake of looking at two things that share a pattern

02:19.060 --> 02:22.300
and deciding they are, like, physically identical.

02:22.420 --> 02:23.220
Which they aren't.

02:23.320 --> 02:23.500
Right.

02:23.740 --> 02:29.040
Human thought is not literally the exact same physical process as a laser beam firing.

02:29.220 --> 02:29.660
Exactly.

02:30.000 --> 02:32.440
And the other trap they mention is vacuous analogy.

02:32.680 --> 02:33.500
What is that exactly?

02:33.600 --> 02:36.500
That happens when you zoom out so far that everything looks the same,

02:36.860 --> 02:38.900
but the observation becomes totally useless.

02:38.900 --> 02:39.720
Oh, right.

02:39.980 --> 02:42.760
Like if you say, well, everything in the universe is constantly transforming.

02:43.000 --> 02:44.000
Yes, exactly.

02:44.100 --> 02:47.160
You say, therefore, everything is one big transformation.

02:47.720 --> 02:49.960
You haven't actually explained anything with that.

02:50.060 --> 02:50.240
Yeah.

02:50.360 --> 02:51.920
It has zero predictive power.

02:51.980 --> 02:52.120
Right.

02:52.380 --> 02:55.700
It's a philosophical bumper sticker, not a scientific framework.

02:55.920 --> 02:56.340
Well said.

02:56.520 --> 02:56.700
Yeah.

02:56.960 --> 03:01.760
So our mission today for this deep dive is to avoid those traps.

03:02.260 --> 03:07.280
We are going to treat this as the ultimate cross-disciplinary puzzle.

03:07.440 --> 03:08.280
I like that framing.

03:08.280 --> 03:12.380
We want to find the rigorous mathematical and structural connections

03:12.380 --> 03:16.660
without blurring the distinct physical realities of each domain.

03:16.960 --> 03:18.260
So we need the mechanics first.

03:18.680 --> 03:19.100
Exactly.

03:19.340 --> 03:19.460
Yeah.

03:19.540 --> 03:24.160
Before we can apply this principle to black holes or, you know, how we learn language,

03:24.340 --> 03:27.920
we need to define the mechanics of the operation itself.

03:28.180 --> 03:31.760
So what actually is an admissibility-constrained collapse?

03:31.940 --> 03:32.900
Let's build the blueprint.

03:33.620 --> 03:36.980
The framework requires four distinct elements to be present.

03:36.980 --> 03:37.380
Okay.

03:37.520 --> 03:38.120
Four elements.

03:38.440 --> 03:40.580
First, you need an admissibility region.

03:41.140 --> 03:43.680
Now, this isn't necessarily a physical place.

03:43.800 --> 03:43.960
Right.

03:44.020 --> 03:44.580
It's more abstract.

03:44.800 --> 03:44.940
Yeah.

03:45.000 --> 03:48.240
It's a bounded space with a specific constraint structure.

03:48.840 --> 03:54.960
Think of it as a territory protected by a very specific filter or membrane that dictates the rules of entry.

03:54.960 --> 03:55.500
Okay.

03:55.700 --> 03:58.020
So a bounded region with strict rules.

03:58.520 --> 03:58.920
Got it.

03:59.160 --> 04:01.100
The second element is a perturbation.

04:01.460 --> 04:02.240
It's like an input.

04:02.480 --> 04:02.780
Exactly.

04:02.940 --> 04:08.460
It's an incoming event, a piece of data, a physical particle, maybe a new idea that approaches the region.

04:08.660 --> 04:08.780
Right.

04:08.920 --> 04:13.640
And for anything to happen, this perturbation must pass a local compatibility test.

04:13.880 --> 04:16.680
It has to match the shape of the membrane's constraint.

04:16.680 --> 04:19.940
So if the perturbation clears the filter, what happens next?

04:20.300 --> 04:23.140
That triggers the third element, which is the collapse operator.

04:23.280 --> 04:24.080
The collapse operator.

04:24.240 --> 04:24.520
Right.

04:24.720 --> 04:26.300
This is the moment of transformation.

04:26.940 --> 04:29.580
The system doesn't just passively absorb the input.

04:29.980 --> 04:35.720
It completely and recursively reorganizes its internal structure to accommodate it.

04:35.800 --> 04:38.140
So it physically or logically changes?

04:38.420 --> 04:38.720
Yes.

04:38.720 --> 04:42.600
The boundary between the input and the system dissolves.

04:43.280 --> 04:46.520
And finally, you get the fourth element, which is a stable output.

04:46.820 --> 04:47.280
So a new normal.

04:47.600 --> 04:50.500
The system settles into a new normal configuration.

04:51.060 --> 04:54.720
But, and this is the vital part, it must preserve a core invariant.

04:55.380 --> 04:58.000
An invariant, meaning something that doesn't change.

04:58.180 --> 04:58.400
Right.

04:58.860 --> 05:07.740
Throughout all this chaotic reorganization, some fundamental property, be it total energy, genetic lineage, or logical truth, has to survive intact.

05:07.740 --> 05:10.220
Okay, I have to pause you there and push back a little.

05:10.700 --> 05:19.960
Because if you describe it purely as, you know, input, rules, reorganization, and output, doesn't that describe almost every process in the universe?

05:20.240 --> 05:21.660
It can sound that way at first.

05:21.900 --> 05:23.340
Let's take my apartment's thermostat.

05:23.760 --> 05:26.000
The room gets cold, that's an incoming perturbation.

05:26.100 --> 05:26.280
Right.

05:26.620 --> 05:32.100
The thermostat has a rule, the membrane, that says, if temp drops below 68, activate.

05:32.340 --> 05:33.320
Okay, I see where you're going.

05:33.320 --> 05:38.880
The system reorganizes by firing up the furnace, and the stable output is a warm room.

05:39.260 --> 05:41.000
The invariant is the baseline temperature.

05:41.120 --> 05:42.960
Doesn't that fit the four steps perfectly?

05:43.340 --> 05:46.180
That is the exact critique someone should level at this theory.

05:46.380 --> 05:51.800
But the framework actually anticipates it, and the answer is that a thermostat absolutely fails the test.

05:52.100 --> 05:52.420
Really?

05:52.880 --> 05:53.380
How so?

05:53.620 --> 06:01.180
To qualify as this generalized reduction operator, a system must meet necessary and sufficient conditions that a thermostat lacks.

06:01.180 --> 06:04.640
A thermostat is what engineers call a bang-bang controller.

06:05.000 --> 06:06.800
Meaning it just flips a switch on and off?

06:06.880 --> 06:07.120
Yes.

06:07.460 --> 06:13.680
It filters outputs based on a constraint, but it does not recursively restructure its own state space.

06:13.760 --> 06:14.200
Oh, I see.

06:14.560 --> 06:17.120
When a thermostat turns off, it hasn't evolved.

06:17.700 --> 06:21.020
Its future possibilities haven't fundamentally changed or narrowed.

06:21.140 --> 06:23.320
It just resets to its previous state.

06:23.460 --> 06:24.540
It's trapped in a loop.

06:24.720 --> 06:25.360
Okay, okay.

06:25.760 --> 06:29.980
What if I compress a high-resolution photograph into a tiny JPEG?

06:29.980 --> 06:31.340
Okay, let's look at that.

06:31.480 --> 06:32.760
That's definitely a one-way trip.

06:33.120 --> 06:38.760
I'm taking a huge amount of data, passing it through an algorithm, the membrane, and reorganizing it into a smaller file.

06:39.160 --> 06:40.940
Compressing a JPEG is a projection.

06:41.580 --> 06:45.120
It throws away data to force the image into a smaller size.

06:45.660 --> 06:47.340
But it fails the invariant test.

06:47.440 --> 06:47.860
It does.

06:47.980 --> 06:48.180
Yeah.

06:48.360 --> 06:55.200
It doesn't propagate what the framework calls a transportable invariant that downstream processes can use to constrain their own futures.

06:55.520 --> 06:58.740
You lose the structural integrity of the original data.

06:58.740 --> 07:00.000
So it's just lossy.

07:00.360 --> 07:01.380
Let me try one more.

07:01.600 --> 07:04.600
I take a wine glass and drop it on a tile floor.

07:05.200 --> 07:05.940
It shatters.

07:06.240 --> 07:06.500
Okay.

07:06.680 --> 07:07.400
There's a region.

07:07.620 --> 07:10.180
There's a perturbation, the floor hitting the glass.

07:10.400 --> 07:10.600
Okay.

07:10.600 --> 07:14.760
And there is an undeniable, irreversible reorganization of the structure.

07:14.940 --> 07:17.240
And that is a pure transformation through destruction.

07:17.560 --> 07:17.820
Right.

07:17.820 --> 07:23.080
When a glass shatters, no coherent, usable constraint survives the collapse.

07:23.080 --> 07:24.640
The glassness is gone.

07:25.060 --> 07:29.220
The invariant isn't preserved in a way that guides the next step of the system's evolution.

07:29.500 --> 07:31.580
It simply becomes debris.

07:31.580 --> 07:34.520
So mere constraint or mere transformation isn't enough.

07:34.620 --> 07:35.040
Exactly.

07:35.220 --> 07:38.840
It requires a specific kind of structured irreversible evolution.

07:39.080 --> 07:41.940
So it's not just reacting to something and it's not just breaking apart.

07:42.520 --> 07:48.880
It has to be permanently committing to a new geometry of possibilities while keeping its core identity alive.

07:49.040 --> 07:50.000
You nailed it.

07:50.000 --> 07:55.500
When I was looking through the notes, the example that really clarified this for me was biological development.

07:55.640 --> 07:57.040
Oh, that's a perfect one.

07:57.140 --> 07:57.320
Yeah.

07:57.480 --> 08:01.320
If you look at a fertilized egg, it starts with total, vast potential.

08:01.600 --> 08:02.700
It can become anything.

08:03.020 --> 08:05.460
That's a magnificent example to ground us.

08:05.860 --> 08:10.000
As that single cell divides, it undergoes a cascade of admissibility collapses.

08:10.740 --> 08:10.960
Right.

08:11.060 --> 08:11.760
It specializes.

08:11.820 --> 08:14.000
It goes through cell fate determination, then organogenesis.

08:15.060 --> 08:18.960
At every single step, it restricts its future possibilities.

08:18.960 --> 08:27.620
Once a cluster of stem cells collapses into the fate of being a heart cell, it cannot reverse course and decide to be a liver cell.

08:28.080 --> 08:30.680
It reorganizes its internal state space.

08:30.800 --> 08:30.940
Yeah.

08:31.020 --> 08:33.040
And its new normal is being cardiac tissue.

08:33.200 --> 08:33.760
Exactly.

08:34.060 --> 08:37.400
But the invariant, the transportable invariant, is its genetic lineage.

08:37.960 --> 08:39.760
The DNA survives the collapse.

08:40.240 --> 08:44.320
The continuity of the organism is preserved even as its possibilities narrow.

08:44.540 --> 08:45.460
That's the distinction.

08:45.460 --> 08:49.700
It narrows its future while remaining a coherent functioning system.

08:50.060 --> 08:52.040
It's so elegant when you frame it that way.

08:52.440 --> 09:00.640
And that biological narrowing sets us up perfectly to look at the absolute purest, most mathematically pristine version of this principle.

09:00.800 --> 09:01.020
Okay.

09:01.120 --> 09:01.600
Let's go there.

09:01.860 --> 09:08.780
To see it stripped of all physical messiness, we have to look at the bedrock of theoretical computer science.

09:08.780 --> 09:12.740
We are talking about the untyped lambda calculus.

09:13.060 --> 09:13.220
Right.

09:13.340 --> 09:13.520
Okay.

09:14.060 --> 09:20.900
For those who aren't deep into the weeds of theoretical math, lambda calculus was introduced by Alonzo Church back in the 1930s.

09:20.980 --> 09:21.440
Yes.

09:21.600 --> 09:31.720
We don't need to get bogged down in the Greek symbols on a chalkboard, but we do need to understand how it operates because the paper argues that this math is the holy grail of admissibility.

09:32.560 --> 09:35.880
Lambda calculus is essentially a universal model of computation.

09:35.880 --> 09:41.700
It proves that you can compute any salvable problem using just three incredibly simple building blocks.

09:41.860 --> 09:42.320
Just three.

09:42.440 --> 09:43.000
Just three.

09:43.260 --> 09:45.220
Variables, abstractions, and application.

09:45.400 --> 09:45.580
Okay.

09:45.620 --> 09:46.340
Let's break those down.

09:46.400 --> 09:48.120
A variable is just a placeholder, right?

09:48.160 --> 09:48.980
Like X or Y.

09:49.100 --> 09:49.260
Yeah.

09:49.320 --> 09:51.520
It's an empty slot waiting for a value.

09:51.960 --> 09:52.240
Yes.

09:52.480 --> 09:53.480
Think of it as a receptacle.

09:53.620 --> 09:55.960
Then you have an abstraction, which is a function.

09:56.040 --> 09:56.540
A function.

09:57.140 --> 09:58.020
Like rule.

09:58.020 --> 10:02.760
An abstraction takes a variable and defines a strict rule for what to do with it.

10:03.560 --> 10:08.280
Imagine a rule that says, take whatever is in the X slot and add 5 to it.

10:08.460 --> 10:09.020
Simple enough.

10:09.280 --> 10:14.060
The abstraction is the protective boundary around that rule waiting for someone to hand it a number.

10:14.360 --> 10:20.320
And the third piece, the application, is the moment I actually walk up to your function and hand it the number 2.

10:20.320 --> 10:24.900
And the instant you hand it the number 2, you trigger what is known as a beta reduction.

10:25.020 --> 10:25.540
Beta reduction.

10:25.820 --> 10:31.380
In the framework of our paper, beta reduction is the ultimate perfect admissibility collapse.

10:31.960 --> 10:38.280
I want to focus on the mechanism of this beta reduction because it's not just a machine spitting out an answer.

10:38.740 --> 10:42.000
The math itself physically changes shape in a way.

10:42.440 --> 10:44.420
The term essentially swallows its argument.

10:44.680 --> 10:46.320
It absorbs the input completely.

10:46.620 --> 10:46.840
Right.

10:46.840 --> 10:54.460
The function takes your number 2, replaces every instance of X inside itself with that 2, and then the boundary of the abstraction dissolves.

10:54.520 --> 10:55.380
It just vanishes.

10:55.660 --> 10:55.860
Yes.

10:56.160 --> 11:01.460
The equation collapses from take X and add 5, where X is 2, into just 7.

11:01.860 --> 11:04.840
It reorganizes into a simpler evaluated form.

11:05.140 --> 11:07.260
It eats the map and becomes a new shape.

11:07.380 --> 11:07.760
Exactly.

11:08.320 --> 11:13.400
And the reason this is so critical is because of something called the Church-Rosser confluence theorem.

11:13.620 --> 11:15.440
Oh, this theorem is beautiful.

11:15.720 --> 11:16.300
It really is.

11:16.300 --> 11:19.600
It's one of those things that feels almost too elegant to be true.

11:20.080 --> 11:28.600
It says that if you have a massive, monstrously complex piece of code with hundreds of different functions, that could be beta reduced.

11:28.720 --> 11:30.460
Like a giant tree of equations.

11:30.780 --> 11:30.960
Yeah.

11:31.380 --> 11:34.420
It fundamentally does not matter which order you tackle them in.

11:34.620 --> 11:37.520
You could start reducing functions on the left side of the equation.

11:37.520 --> 11:41.600
Imagine I could start on the right, and someone else could pick functions at random from the middle.

11:41.920 --> 11:42.900
And it wouldn't mess it up.

11:42.980 --> 11:49.600
As long as we all follow the strict rules of beta reduction, all roads lead to the exact same destination.

11:49.600 --> 11:55.260
We will all eventually arrive at the exact same unique stable end point.

11:55.720 --> 11:57.220
Which is called the beta normal form.

11:57.300 --> 11:57.460
Right.

11:57.780 --> 12:04.220
The invariant that is preserved through all that chaotic reduction is the underlying logical truth of the computation.

12:04.940 --> 12:06.620
The trajectory doesn't matter.

12:06.620 --> 12:08.620
The truth is mathematically bulletproof.

12:08.960 --> 12:11.100
That is the magic of the confluence theorem.

12:11.440 --> 12:17.760
But because we are exploring a principle of constraints, we also have to look at what happens when the constraint fails.

12:17.760 --> 12:20.120
Yes, the dark side of computation.

12:20.480 --> 12:22.760
The paper brings up the omega fixed-plant combinator.

12:23.620 --> 12:28.940
The omega combinator is a fascinating piece of code because it creates a nightmare scenario.

12:30.360 --> 12:30.880
Divergence.

12:31.080 --> 12:32.840
Divergence, meaning it never finishes.

12:33.040 --> 12:33.440
Exactly.

12:33.660 --> 12:37.700
It is a function that is designed to feed itself to itself forever.

12:37.960 --> 12:41.200
Like a snake eating its own tail, but the tail keeps regenerating.

12:41.200 --> 12:49.980
In the language of the admissibility schema, it's a region that accepts a perturbation, triggers a collapse operator, but never reaches a stable output.

12:50.080 --> 12:51.700
It never hits that beta normal form.

12:51.820 --> 12:52.120
Never.

12:52.360 --> 12:54.780
It is an admissibility loop with no attractor.

12:55.000 --> 12:59.480
It just continuously, frantically reorganizes itself without ever resolving.

12:59.700 --> 13:04.360
It's the theoretical math version of the spinning beach ball of death on your computer.

13:04.560 --> 13:05.660
That's a great way to put it.

13:05.740 --> 13:06.940
It just never compiles.

13:07.380 --> 13:07.500
Yeah.

13:07.500 --> 13:11.500
Now, there is one more mathematical concept here that I found completely staggering.

13:11.980 --> 13:13.320
The Curry-Howard correspondence.

13:13.420 --> 13:13.740
Oh, yeah.

13:13.780 --> 13:16.540
When I was reading this, I had to stare at the wall for a good five minutes.

13:17.280 --> 13:21.260
It basically proves that computer programming and mathematical proofs aren't just similar.

13:21.640 --> 13:23.020
They were exactly the same thing.

13:23.280 --> 13:25.940
It is a profound realization in mathematics.

13:26.920 --> 13:33.100
Curry-Howard shows that the types in a programming language correspond directly to logical propositions in a proof.

13:33.220 --> 13:34.740
The programs themselves are the proofs.

13:34.740 --> 13:35.140
Yes.

13:35.620 --> 13:39.620
And the act of running the program, the beta reduction we just talked about, is identical

13:39.620 --> 13:44.100
to the process of normalizing or simplifying a mathematical proof.

13:44.560 --> 13:49.220
So if I write a program that takes an input A and an input B and returns a pair of A and B,

13:49.720 --> 13:50.980
I haven't just written code.

13:50.980 --> 13:59.060
I have literally constructed the logical proof that if A is true and B is true, then A, A, N, D, B is true.

13:59.180 --> 14:05.160
You've discovered that logic and computation are just two different dialects, spoken by the same underlying master grammar.

14:05.380 --> 14:05.660
Wow.

14:05.920 --> 14:11.740
The rules of admissibility govern what is computationally true just as strictly as they govern what is logically true.

14:11.740 --> 14:17.260
But the author of this paper doesn't just rest on the laurels of established math in the 1930s.

14:17.260 --> 14:26.240
They introduce a speculative, highly visual, new theoretical framework to explain how this math actually lives and breathes.

14:26.820 --> 14:27.800
The SpherePop model.

14:28.000 --> 14:28.600
Yeah, SpherePop.

14:28.720 --> 14:30.480
It's a geometric operational semantics.

14:31.180 --> 14:37.880
And SpherePop asks us to completely abandon the idea of computer code as invisible text scrolling on a screen.

14:37.880 --> 14:45.880
SpherePop attempts to externalize the hidden process of computation into literal, spatial, multidimensional geometry.

14:46.340 --> 14:47.460
Okay, walk me through that.

14:47.580 --> 14:56.060
Instead of lines of text replacing other lines of text in a void, this model visualizes every single piece of code as a topological bubble.

14:56.220 --> 14:57.020
A literal bubble.

14:57.340 --> 14:59.580
This is the point in the notes where the visuals really help me.

15:00.020 --> 15:01.960
Every bubble in SpherePop has three things.

15:02.060 --> 15:02.240
Right.

15:02.720 --> 15:06.820
It has an interior, which holds the latent expressions or the code waiting to run.

15:06.820 --> 15:12.860
It has a membrane, which is the constraint filter, deciding what other bubbles are allowed to pass inside.

15:13.360 --> 15:14.880
And most importantly, it has a history.

15:15.340 --> 15:17.280
Let's focus on the interaction between these bubbles.

15:17.600 --> 15:19.340
Imagine one bubble approaching another.

15:19.520 --> 15:20.620
Like floating through space.

15:20.840 --> 15:21.140
Right.

15:22.160 --> 15:25.720
The membrane of the receiving bubble acts as the local compatibility test.

15:25.920 --> 15:27.640
It interrogates the incoming bubble.

15:27.980 --> 15:32.660
If the incoming bubble's geometry doesn't match the constraints, it bounces off.

15:33.040 --> 15:33.760
Nothing happens.

15:33.880 --> 15:34.740
It just rejects it.

15:34.740 --> 15:40.960
But if it does match, the membrane opens up, swallows the incoming bubble, and the interior reorganizes.

15:41.120 --> 15:43.600
So it's a spatial visualization of the beta reduction.

15:43.880 --> 15:44.360
Exactly.

15:44.560 --> 15:47.200
I tried to map this onto something physical to make it click.

15:48.280 --> 15:53.940
It reminds me of a biological cell membrane interacting with a very specific protein in the bloodstream.

15:54.080 --> 15:55.520
That's a very solid analogy.

15:55.520 --> 15:57.460
The cell membrane is the constraint.

15:57.780 --> 16:07.720
It rejects almost everything, but when the exact right protein floats by, it binds to a receptor, gets pulled inside, and then the cell reorganizes its internal machinery.

16:08.560 --> 16:10.500
Maybe it changes its DNA expression.

16:10.780 --> 16:10.980
Right.

16:11.240 --> 16:15.160
But the key is that once it does this, it keeps a permanent memory of the event.

16:15.160 --> 16:17.500
The cell is forever changed.

16:17.700 --> 16:23.840
That biological metaphor captures the mechanics perfectly, especially regarding the final element, history.

16:24.060 --> 16:25.400
Why is the history so important?

16:25.660 --> 16:30.360
The author argues that adding that history parameter is what makes the collapse irreversible.

16:30.360 --> 16:39.220
In traditional text-based lambda calculus, once you reduce an equation, the original variables disappear, the history is erased.

16:39.380 --> 16:40.120
You can't undo it.

16:40.240 --> 16:45.480
SpherePop makes the dependency and the history visible as a permanent spatial geometry.

16:45.740 --> 16:47.800
It forces the math to have a pass.

16:47.800 --> 17:02.660
And by giving abstract logic a spatial geometry and a permanent history, SpherePop acts as the theoretical bridge between the timeless, perfect world of pure symbolic math and the irreversible, memory-laden messiness of the physical world.

17:02.920 --> 17:04.540
That bridge is crucial.

17:04.900 --> 17:17.020
Because if computation is just collapsing, history-dependent bubbles, the author takes an enormous leap and argues that human thought, the way you and I are processing this conversation right now, operates on that exact same geometry.

17:17.020 --> 17:21.260
We're moving out of computer science and diving straight into cognitive psychology here.

17:21.340 --> 17:21.440
Yeah.

17:21.840 --> 17:25.020
Specifically, we are looking at the foundational work of Douglas Hofstadter.

17:25.640 --> 17:25.940
Yes.

17:26.320 --> 17:30.300
Hofstadter famously argued that the hidden brain does not function like a calculator.

17:30.800 --> 17:35.020
We do not compute reality using rigid Boolean logic rules.

17:35.520 --> 17:39.640
The fundamental currency of human cognition is analogy-making.

17:40.020 --> 17:45.260
He argues that what we call a concept is actually just a tightly bound bundle of analogies.

17:45.260 --> 17:51.180
And he outlines a process called chunking, which feels so intuitive once you name it.

17:51.280 --> 17:51.860
Oh, absolutely.

17:52.080 --> 17:58.460
When we are infants, the world is just a chaotic storm of raw perceptual features, colors, edges, loud noises.

17:59.040 --> 18:03.560
But over time, our brains compress those small features into a single chunk.

18:03.880 --> 18:05.520
We chunk the features into a concept.

18:05.760 --> 18:05.980
Right.

18:06.240 --> 18:10.440
Then, as we grow, we take a bunch of concepts and compress them into a larger schema.

18:10.700 --> 18:14.420
Now, maps that psychological process onto the geometry of SpherePop.

18:14.420 --> 18:18.460
Chunking is the exact process of nested bubble formation.

18:18.700 --> 18:19.940
The bubbles inside bubbles.

18:20.120 --> 18:20.420
Yes.

18:21.140 --> 18:28.880
Small, chaotic, perceptual bubbles undergo an admissibility test, collapse into each other, and form a larger, stable, conceptual bubble.

18:29.120 --> 18:31.820
The paper defines this as cognitive admissibility.

18:32.500 --> 18:36.580
When I see something new in the world, my brain doesn't just passively record it like a hard drive.

18:36.700 --> 18:37.780
No, it evaluates it.

18:37.780 --> 18:39.960
The new perception acts as a perturbation.

18:40.740 --> 18:43.300
My mind checks it against my existing membranes.

18:43.980 --> 18:49.280
If it causes what the author calls an analogical resonance with a stored chunk, it gets admitted.

18:49.640 --> 18:51.820
Let's trace how that happens in real time.

18:52.180 --> 18:54.900
Think about a child learning to identify animals.

18:55.160 --> 18:55.400
Okay.

18:55.400 --> 18:59.280
At first, the child forms a conceptual bubble for dog.

18:59.740 --> 19:02.580
The constraint membrane for that bubble might be very loose.

19:02.680 --> 19:04.760
It just requires furry and four legs.

19:04.960 --> 19:09.180
So, when the child sees a cat for the first time, the cat perturbation hits the dog membrane.

19:09.360 --> 19:09.800
Exactly.

19:09.900 --> 19:12.460
Because the membrane is loose, the cat passes the test.

19:12.640 --> 19:14.000
Michelle points at the cat and says,

19:14.220 --> 19:14.500
Dog.

19:14.500 --> 19:18.880
The brain has admitted the perception because it resonates analogically.

19:19.020 --> 19:22.160
But as the child interacts more with the world, the constraints tighten.

19:22.660 --> 19:26.320
The child notices the cat meows instead of barks and jumps on the counter.

19:26.480 --> 19:27.540
The geometry changes.

19:27.740 --> 19:30.900
The dog membrane updates to exclude these new behaviors.

19:31.460 --> 19:33.980
A new, separate bubble for cat is formed.

19:34.460 --> 19:38.200
The child's conceptual structure updates through recursive collapse.

19:38.440 --> 19:42.220
There's a researcher cited here named Johansson who takes this even further.

19:42.220 --> 19:46.180
He argues that language acquisition, how we learn to speak,

19:46.500 --> 19:50.180
is primarily a process of reduction rather than pure construction.

19:50.700 --> 19:52.220
That's a fascinating perspective.

19:52.400 --> 19:55.320
We don't build sentences from scratch like laying bricks.

19:56.000 --> 20:00.500
We take in an enormous amount of messy, overcomplicated sensory data.

20:00.960 --> 20:05.700
And then we ruthlessly eliminate the irregularities to find the stable grammatical rules.

20:05.940 --> 20:08.500
It forces us to invert how we think about learning.

20:08.500 --> 20:13.920
We naturally assume learning is additive, that we are taking an empty brain and filling it with facts.

20:14.040 --> 20:15.560
Like pouring water into a glass.

20:15.800 --> 20:16.300
Exactly.

20:16.760 --> 20:21.300
But Johansson and this overarching framework suggests that cognition only functions

20:21.300 --> 20:25.100
because it continuously reduces the number of admissible trajectories.

20:25.660 --> 20:29.100
We learn by pouring away the massive tree of things that don't fit

20:29.100 --> 20:31.400
until only the stable invariant remains.

20:31.620 --> 20:35.560
I see the structural similarity, but I want to push back on this on behalf of the listener.

20:35.680 --> 20:36.160
Please do.

20:36.160 --> 20:40.220
Because if human analogy is just an exact mathematical reduction,

20:40.380 --> 20:42.220
like a piece of code swallowing a variable,

20:42.540 --> 20:45.380
how do you explain the messiness of human communication?

20:45.800 --> 20:46.220
What do you mean?

20:46.780 --> 20:48.200
How do you explain a misunderstanding?

20:49.120 --> 20:52.080
Or even better, how do you explain poetry or metaphor?

20:53.460 --> 20:57.440
A great poem is powerful precisely because it doesn't compile perfectly.

20:57.880 --> 20:59.840
It's delightfully inexact.

20:59.840 --> 21:04.840
That inexactness is the brilliant distinction between the rigid constraints of a computer program

21:04.840 --> 21:07.180
and the flexibility of a cognitive bubble.

21:07.400 --> 21:08.260
Okay, how so?

21:08.580 --> 21:11.720
Offshatter introduces the mechanism of semantic slippage.

21:12.280 --> 21:16.400
While lambda calculus requires a perfect match to trigger a beta reduction,

21:16.940 --> 21:20.580
human cognitive membranes can perform a fuzzy collapse.

21:20.840 --> 21:21.700
A fuzzy collapse.

21:21.740 --> 21:25.060
That sounds like a contradiction in terms, but I think I see where you're going.

21:25.060 --> 21:30.120
When you encounter a metaphor, the incoming perturbation doesn't perfectly match any single

21:30.120 --> 21:35.060
conceptual bubble you have, but it matches enough of the constraints to trigger a partial

21:35.060 --> 21:35.580
collapse.

21:35.760 --> 21:37.220
It sort of wedges itself in.

21:37.340 --> 21:37.560
Right.

21:37.960 --> 21:42.840
The membrane admits the concept, but leaves some of the internal structure open and unresolved.

21:43.280 --> 21:47.820
That semantic slippage, the gap between the literal meaning and the analogical resonance,

21:48.040 --> 21:49.360
is where creativity lives.

21:49.360 --> 21:54.640
The author actually uses this to explain the sheer miracle that we can communicate with

21:54.640 --> 21:55.400
each other at all.

21:56.080 --> 22:00.840
The paper describes human communication as compressed semantic transport.

22:01.300 --> 22:02.660
Let's break that down mechanically.

22:03.380 --> 22:08.540
When I want to convey a complex idea to you, I cannot transmit my entire neural state.

22:08.700 --> 22:09.920
I wish you could sometimes.

22:10.040 --> 22:10.740
It would be faster.

22:10.880 --> 22:11.180
Right.

22:11.180 --> 22:17.440
But instead, I have to compress a massive, multidimensional, conceptual bubble into a

22:17.440 --> 22:20.320
tiny, linear string of acoustic vibrations.

22:21.100 --> 22:21.500
Words.

22:21.840 --> 22:24.420
I compress my bubble into an mp3, basically.

22:24.820 --> 22:26.840
I send the words through the air and they hit your ear.

22:27.380 --> 22:29.560
But you don't just receive the meaning cassively.

22:29.660 --> 22:30.780
No, I have to unpack it.

22:30.800 --> 22:34.760
You have to take that highly compressed acoustic perturbation and add water.

22:35.080 --> 22:40.100
You have to rehydrate the meaning inside your own brain using your own stored history of

22:40.100 --> 22:40.380
bubbles.

22:40.380 --> 22:45.480
And that transport only succeeds if your bubble topology is compatible enough with mine to

22:45.480 --> 22:47.500
allow for a successful membrane collapse.

22:47.860 --> 22:52.040
So if our lived experiences and our internal constraint structures are wildly different,

22:52.420 --> 22:53.840
the perturbation bounces off.

22:54.180 --> 22:58.220
Which perfectly explains why you can read a profound book at age 15 and think it's boring,

22:58.660 --> 23:03.020
and then read the exact same words at age 40, and it shatters your worldview.

23:03.300 --> 23:04.680
The words didn't change at all.

23:04.860 --> 23:06.120
The words didn't change.

23:06.120 --> 23:12.680
Your internal constraint membrane evolved to a point where it could finally admit the perturbation.

23:12.680 --> 23:17.340
It also explains why some idioms are literally untranslatable.

23:17.580 --> 23:18.880
Right, cultural idioms.

23:19.000 --> 23:25.240
If I try to translate a highly specific cultural joke into another language, the receiving language might not have a topological bubble

23:25.240 --> 23:28.020
shaped to receive that specific semantic geometry.

23:28.020 --> 23:34.900
We are constantly trying to find a topology-preserving reduction across incompatible semantic manifolds.

23:35.420 --> 23:37.280
When it works, it's a fuzzy collapse.

23:37.840 --> 23:39.400
When it fails, we get a misunderstanding.

23:39.800 --> 23:43.160
Which brings us to one of the most compelling parts of the entire document.

23:43.800 --> 23:48.440
What happens when this process breaks down not in a human mind, but in an artificial one?

23:48.440 --> 23:50.800
Ah, AI hallucinations.

23:50.880 --> 23:51.120
Yes.

23:51.340 --> 23:54.780
The paper takes this framework and applies it to AI hallucination.

23:55.180 --> 24:00.580
And to do it, it brings in some heavy mathematical artillery called sheaf semantics in the H1 coenology group.

24:00.720 --> 24:03.900
This is perhaps the most elegant practical application in the paper.

24:04.280 --> 24:07.500
To understand it, we need to understand what a sheaf is.

24:07.880 --> 24:08.160
Okay.

24:08.160 --> 24:14.160
In algebraic topology, a sheaf is a mathematical tool designed to track locally defined data

24:14.160 --> 24:19.720
and determine if that local data can be seamlessly stitched together into a coherent global whole.

24:19.980 --> 24:22.500
I need a visual for that, if I'm trying to picture a sheaf.

24:22.560 --> 24:28.200
Imagine you were trying to map a massive, sprawling city, but you don't have a satellite.

24:28.500 --> 24:28.740
Okay.

24:28.980 --> 24:34.340
You only have a thousand highly detailed maps of individual neighborhoods drawn by different people.

24:35.320 --> 24:37.560
Locally, every single map is perfect.

24:37.560 --> 24:40.820
The streets connect properly, the addresses are right.

24:40.920 --> 24:42.200
Okay, I have my local patches.

24:42.480 --> 24:47.020
Now, you try to glue those neighborhood maps together to create a master map of the entire city,

24:47.200 --> 24:50.700
but as you overlap the edges, you realize the roads don't line up.

24:50.800 --> 24:52.480
Oh, like a puzzle with the wrong pieces.

24:52.780 --> 24:53.060
Yes.

24:53.500 --> 24:57.820
A street on one map flows north, but on the adjoining map, it flows east.

24:58.400 --> 25:04.220
That mathematical failure to glue local patches into a global structure is called an obstruction.

25:04.520 --> 25:05.080
An obstruction.

25:05.080 --> 25:12.040
And in topology, the presence of that obstruction is measured by something called the first etch cohomology group,

25:12.440 --> 25:13.720
often written as H1.

25:13.880 --> 25:19.880
So if H1 is not zero, it means you have a fundamental structural flaw preventing a global reality.

25:20.140 --> 25:20.660
Exactly.

25:20.660 --> 25:30.580
How does this explain why a sophisticated large language model suddenly invents a fake court case and cites non-existent legal precedents with absolute confidence?

25:31.080 --> 25:34.680
AI hallucination is perfectly modeled as a sheaf-gluing failure.

25:35.500 --> 25:37.680
We'll have to look at how an LLM generates text.

25:38.100 --> 25:42.020
It is predicting the next most likely token based on its training data.

25:42.020 --> 25:44.340
Locally, the grammar is flawless.

25:45.060 --> 25:46.920
The sentence structure makes sense.

25:47.160 --> 25:50.880
The localized semantic patch is totally consistent and admissible.

25:51.100 --> 25:51.320
Right.

25:51.440 --> 25:53.140
It sounds incredibly smart in a vacuum.

25:53.340 --> 26:00.200
But when you step back and try to assemble those local sentences into a global representation of actual factual world knowledge,

26:00.880 --> 26:02.240
you hit a structural obstruction.

26:02.420 --> 26:03.380
The roads don't line up.

26:03.380 --> 26:08.160
The AI cannot glue the patches together because it lacks a global constraint membrane.

26:08.320 --> 26:10.200
It doesn't actually have a global world model bubble.

26:10.460 --> 26:14.200
It just has overlapping local patches of statistical probability.

26:14.460 --> 26:20.280
So it confidently strings together perfectly logical sentences that, when placed in the real world,

26:20.680 --> 26:24.440
represent complete physical or historical impossibility.

26:24.620 --> 26:31.460
The syntax passes the local admissibility test, but the generated concept fails the global compatibility test.

26:31.460 --> 26:36.600
Viewing hallucination as a topological gluing failure, rather than just saying,

26:36.960 --> 26:41.880
well, the computer made a mistake, completely changes how you understand artificial intelligence.

26:42.120 --> 26:46.580
It's doing exactly what it was designed to do locally, but failing globally.

26:46.800 --> 26:48.980
It's a structural limitation, not a bug.

26:49.200 --> 26:49.560
All right.

26:49.640 --> 26:55.060
So we've spent a lot of time in the realm of single minds, human, and artificial reducing information.

26:55.540 --> 26:59.220
But the real test of a master grammar is whether it scales up.

26:59.240 --> 26:59.460
Right.

26:59.620 --> 27:00.780
Multi-agent systems.

27:00.780 --> 27:04.300
What happens when multiple minds interact in a competitive environment?

27:04.860 --> 27:09.220
The paper takes this exact same mathematical structure and applies it to human strategy.

27:09.540 --> 27:14.800
We are looking at the work of Christina Bicchieri and Oliver Schulte on epistemic game theory.

27:14.960 --> 27:15.160
Okay.

27:15.300 --> 27:15.760
Game theory.

27:15.880 --> 27:19.480
Game theory is essentially the mathematics of interactive decision making.

27:19.840 --> 27:24.120
It's the math of trying to outsmart someone who is actively trying to outsmart you.

27:24.120 --> 27:24.760
Exactly.

27:25.100 --> 27:34.280
And in this context, the authors argue that strategic reasoning is just another form of admissibility-constrained collapse operating on a space of possible futures.

27:34.680 --> 27:35.420
How does that work?

27:35.600 --> 27:41.220
The core mechanism they focus on is the elimination of weakly-dominated strategies.

27:41.220 --> 27:44.140
Let's define that because it's a great concept.

27:44.860 --> 27:54.000
A weakly-dominated strategy is an option on your menu of choices that is objectively worse for you, regardless of what your opponent decides to do.

27:54.440 --> 27:55.720
It's a strategic dead end.

27:55.940 --> 27:56.760
Let's ground it.

27:57.020 --> 28:00.700
Imagine you are driving to a highly important meeting and you have two route options.

28:00.860 --> 28:01.660
Route A and Route B.

28:01.660 --> 28:06.000
Route A takes 20 minutes if there's no traffic and 30 minutes if there is heavy traffic.

28:06.440 --> 28:09.940
Route B takes 40 minutes if there's no traffic and 60 minutes if there is traffic.

28:10.040 --> 28:18.960
Well, no matter what the traffic conditions are, which represents the unpredictable actions of the other drivers, route B is always going to make me later than route A.

28:19.100 --> 28:21.900
So route B is a weakly-dominated strategy.

28:22.480 --> 28:27.800
If I'm a rational actor with all the information, I am never, ever going to choose route B.

28:27.960 --> 28:29.560
And that is the first level of the collapse.

28:29.560 --> 28:32.140
You prune that branch off your decision tree.

28:33.280 --> 28:37.520
But game theory gets interesting when we introduce common reasoning about admissibility.

28:37.740 --> 28:38.300
Common reasoning.

28:38.680 --> 28:41.840
You don't just eliminate bad moves from your own playbook.

28:42.020 --> 28:49.860
You eliminate potential futures based on the assumption that your opponent is also rational and they are also eliminating bad moves from their playbook.

28:50.040 --> 28:52.040
It becomes a recursive loop of assumptions.

28:52.400 --> 28:55.020
I know that I know we aren't going to make stupid moves.

28:55.080 --> 28:56.280
Yes, the mind games.

28:56.280 --> 29:08.020
So if we map this back onto our structural blueprint, the admissibility region is the player's information set everything I know about the game, the rules, and the payoffs.

29:08.140 --> 29:11.760
And the perturbation is a new strategy possibility entering your mind.

29:12.160 --> 29:15.420
The collapse operator is the iterative pruning of the game tree.

29:15.420 --> 29:21.080
You recursively chop off the branches that represent irrational, weakly-dominated choices.

29:21.520 --> 29:27.240
So a complex strategic game is basically just a massive multiplayer sphere pop bubble.

29:27.800 --> 29:32.380
The membrane that decides what gets let in is just human rationality.

29:32.580 --> 29:33.920
That is a brilliant synthesis.

29:34.380 --> 29:41.020
The chaotic tree of infinite possible game moves collapses into a tight, stable topology of rational choices.

29:41.200 --> 29:42.940
It just prunes away all the nonsense.

29:42.940 --> 29:48.580
And just like lambda calculus, we have to ask, what is the invariant being preserved?

29:49.420 --> 29:54.520
Bittieri and Schulte demonstrated that the preserved invariant is representation independence.

29:55.100 --> 29:56.020
Break that down for me.

29:56.060 --> 29:56.680
What does that mean?

29:56.880 --> 30:03.700
In game theory, you can try to solve the game using forward induction reasoning from the first move to the end or backward induction,

30:04.040 --> 30:08.580
where you look at the final payoffs and reason backward to figure out what the first move should be.

30:08.580 --> 30:15.980
Their work shows that whether you look at the game backward or forward, the rational solutions you arrive at are exactly the same,

30:16.060 --> 30:18.760
as long as the common knowledge of admissibility holds.

30:18.860 --> 30:20.940
It's the Church-Rosser confluence theorem again.

30:21.000 --> 30:24.360
It doesn't matter what trajectory you take to solve the game.

30:25.160 --> 30:30.940
Rationality forces the system to collapse into the same stable, normal form.

30:31.200 --> 30:32.660
It's incredibly elegant.

30:32.860 --> 30:35.700
It really connects the math to human behavior.

30:35.700 --> 30:40.740
But, okay, I want to take a breath here, because so far we've been swimming in the realm of information.

30:41.300 --> 30:46.180
We've talked about abstract math, cognitive psychology, and game strategy.

30:46.380 --> 30:47.480
All very conceptual.

30:47.860 --> 30:51.800
It is one thing for human minds and computer code to follow this pattern.

30:52.340 --> 30:53.840
They are logical constructs.

30:54.160 --> 31:02.920
It is an entirely different level of wild to suggest that the foundational hard physics of the universe obeys this exact same geometry.

31:02.920 --> 31:06.100
This is where the paper's grounding is most rigorously tested.

31:06.500 --> 31:10.060
It leaves the realm of abstraction and looks at established empirical physics.

31:10.240 --> 31:11.720
Which feels like a huge leap.

31:11.780 --> 31:12.260
It does.

31:12.480 --> 31:18.980
The first example it brings up is a 2025 paper from APL Quantum concerning something called the quantum dwell time problem.

31:19.160 --> 31:24.120
I read this section of the notes three times to make sure I wasn't hallucinating a sheaf-glowing failure myself.

31:24.200 --> 31:26.280
It is notoriously weird physics.

31:26.620 --> 31:29.080
The problem asks what seems like a very simple question.

31:29.080 --> 31:40.660
You have a cloud of atoms, you fire a single photon at it, the photon can pass straight through, or it can briefly get absorbed, turn into an atomic excitation, and then get re-emitted to continue on its way.

31:40.780 --> 31:41.000
Right.

31:41.540 --> 31:48.680
The researchers wanted to know, how long does the transmitted photon spend inside the atom as an excitation?

31:48.680 --> 31:51.480
It sounds like a straightforward stopwatch problem.

31:52.040 --> 32:00.180
But in certain resonant regimes, specifically where there is superluminal group delay, the mathematics and the measurements yield a mind-bending result.

32:00.380 --> 32:01.300
And what is that result?

32:01.600 --> 32:05.900
The calculated atomic excitation time for a transmitted photon is negative.

32:06.200 --> 32:06.820
Negative time.

32:07.240 --> 32:08.240
Okay, stop the tape.

32:08.340 --> 32:08.620
I know.

32:08.620 --> 32:21.860
We need to unpack this carefully, because the moment someone hears negative time in quantum physics, they think we are talking about time travel, or a particle traveling backward through causality to change the past.

32:21.920 --> 32:23.000
Right, it sounds like sci-fi.

32:23.320 --> 32:29.280
The paper was very careful to put a caveat on this, and we need to clarify it before we lose our grip on reality.

32:29.620 --> 32:31.460
Yes, precision is vital here.

32:31.700 --> 32:34.080
It is absolutely not backward time travel.

32:34.080 --> 32:42.160
The negative time recorded is what quantum physicists classify as an anomalous weak value.

32:42.520 --> 32:45.480
It is an artifact of post-selection interference.

32:45.820 --> 32:46.960
What does that mean mechanically?

32:47.820 --> 32:51.740
How does a stopwatch read less than zero without breaking the universe?

32:52.240 --> 32:57.080
We have to remember, we are dealing with the inherent weirdness of quantum superposition.

32:57.560 --> 33:03.280
Before the photon is definitively measured at the end of its journey, it doesn't take a single path.

33:03.280 --> 33:04.180
It takes all of them, right.

33:04.300 --> 33:09.580
It exists as a wave of probabilities, effectively taking multiple pathways simultaneously.

33:10.280 --> 33:13.740
In pathway one, it zips through the atomic cloud without interacting at all.

33:14.120 --> 33:17.700
In pathway two, it gets absorbed, excites the atom, and is re-emitted.

33:17.840 --> 33:19.540
So it's doing both until we look at it.

33:19.860 --> 33:20.260
Precisely.

33:20.520 --> 33:24.700
Now, because these are probability waves, they can interfere with each other, just like ripples on a pond.

33:24.920 --> 33:28.680
If the crest of one wave hits the trough of another, they cancel each other out.

33:29.000 --> 33:30.300
This is destructive interference.

33:30.600 --> 33:31.100
Okay, I'm following.

33:31.100 --> 33:38.460
